06580nam a22008295i 9783110789690DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107896907 a10.1515/97831107896902doi  a(DE-B1597)619274  a(OCoLC)1371573808  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE  aMD 89202rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122569:00aOn the Social History of Persecution /ced. by Christian Gerlach. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VI, 291 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Social histories of persecution and mass violence -- tLabor -- tStrategies of survival: Genocide and Armenian deportee labor, 1915-1918 -- tComparing Jewish labor in Poland, 1942-1945, and Armenian labor in the Ottoman Empire, 1915-1918 -- tFamily -- tThe family under duress: A male perspective -- t"He was in our home like our own child": Discourses of surrogacy and family relations after the Holocaust -- tDisplacement -- tStrangers in a strange land: Refugees in Belarusian society under German occupation (1941-1944) -- tCaught between the guerrilla and the colonial state: Refugee life in Northern Mozambique during the Independence War (1964-1974) -- tSpace -- tSpace and place: Placing everyday life during the Holocaust -- tHiding in the attic: Sounds and social situation -- tCollective action -- tAuditory quarrels, rage and collective action: A street singer and his audience within the web of the ghetto society -- tPeople Fell Like Flies: How Yiddish songs document history and collective action during the Holocaust in the Soviet Union -- tMass violence as a social process -- tA local history of the Sobibór death camp and Nazi occupation -- tSociety after violence -- tOrphans building homes: Forgotten remnants of the Armenian deportations in South Jordan -- tList of authors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis multi-disciplinary volume is one of the few collections about social change covering various cases of mass violence and genocide. In life under persecution, social relations and social structures were not absent and not simply replaced by an ethno-racial order. The studies in this book show the influence of social structures like gender, age and class on life under persecution. Exploring practices in family and labor relations and of collective action, they counter claims of an atomization of society or total uprootedness of victims. Despite being exposed to poverty and want and under the permanent threat of political violence, persecuted people tried to develop their own agency. Case studies are about the Jewish and Armenian persecutions, Rwanda, the war of decolonization in Mozambique and civilian refuges in Belarus during World War II. The authors are a mix of experienced scholars and young researchers.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Schweizerischer Nationalfonds (SNF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4a20. Jahrhundert. 4aGenozid. 4aWeltgeschichte.  a20th century, global history.  aGenocide.1 aAleksiun, Natalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCerovic, Masha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerlach, Christian , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGerlach, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHock, Nikita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaiser, Hilmar, econt